1. Collections (List, Set, Map)
Collections are used to store multiple items. In Apex, these are almost always heap-allocated using the new keyword.


// List: An ordered collection that allows duplicates
List<String> fruitList = new List<String>();
fruitList.add('Apple');
fruitList.add('Orange');

// Set: An unordered collection of unique elements
Set<Id> accountIds = new Set<Id>();
accountIds.add('0018000000abcde');

// Map: A collection of key-value pairs (Unique keys)
Map<Id, Account> accountMap = new Map<Id, Account>();


2. Loops and Control Flow
These structures allow you to iterate through data and apply logic based on specific conditions.

For Loop
There are several types of for loops, but the List/Set iteration is the most common in Salesforce development.

// Iterating over a list
for (String fruit : fruitList) {
    System.debug('Current fruit: ' + fruit);
}

// Traditional for loop
for (Integer i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
    System.debug('Counter is: ' + i);
}

If / Else Statement
Used for basic conditional branching.

Integer score = 85;

if (score >= 90) {
    System.debug('Grade: A');
} else if (score >= 80) {
    System.debug('Grade: B');
} else {
    System.debug('Grade: C');
}

Switch Statement (Case)
Apex uses the switch on syntax rather than a traditional "case" keyword found in other languages.

String leadStatus = 'Open';

switch on leadStatus {
    when 'Open' {
        System.debug('Keep calling!');
    }
    when 'Closed - Converted', 'Closed - Not Converted' {
        System.debug('Work is finished.');
    }
    when else {
        System.debug('Status unknown.');
    }
}

3. SOQL (Salesforce Object Query Language)
SOQL is used to read records from the database. You wrap the query in square brackets [].

// Querying a list of records
List<Account> teaAccounts = [SELECT Id, Name, Industry
                             FROM Account
                             WHERE Industry = 'Agriculture'
                             LIMIT 10];

// Using a variable in a query (Bind Variable)
String targetName = 'Acme Corp';
Account myAcc = [SELECT Id, Name FROM Account WHERE Name = :targetName LIMIT 1];

Pro-Tip: The "SOQL For Loop"
In Salesforce, it is a best practice to combine your query and your loop to avoid hitting governor limits (specifically heap size limits).

Java
// This is the most efficient way to process large sets of records
for (Account acc : [SELECT Id, Name FROM Account WHERE CreatedDate = TODAY]) {
    // Logic for each account goes here
    System.debug('Processing: ' + acc.Name);
}
